# Code owners.
#
# This file only has teeth if `main` has branch protection with "Require review
# from Code Owners" enabled. Without that it is documentation. See
# CONTRIBUTING.md ("How a release actually reaches npm") for why that matters.
#
# The point is not to gate every change — it's to make the RELEASE MECHANISM
# itself reviewable. npm's trusted publisher is bound to a repo + workflow
# filename, not to the workflow's contents: whoever can change release.yml on
# main can publish arbitrary bytes as @hedgerow/*. In a repo where agents author
# much of the code, that file deserves a different level of attention than a
# component.
#
# "Why is this PR editing release.yml?" is a question worth stopping on.
# "Do I want to release 0.2.0?" mostly isn't — which is why the npm-publish
# environment deliberately has no required reviewer.

# Everything, by default.
*                           @crsren

# The release mechanism: what publishes, how, and with what credentials.
/.github/workflows/         @crsren
/.github/CODEOWNERS         @crsren
/scripts/                   @crsren
/.changeset/config.json     @crsren

# What each package ships to npm — `files`, `exports`, `publishConfig`.
/packages/*/package.json    @crsren

# The committed public API + behavioural contract. A diff here is the evidence
# for the version bump, so it should never change without someone reading it.
/api-report/                @crsren
